---
import MarketingLayout from "../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="MailAtlas: Local Email I/O for AI Agents and Data Apps"
  description="MailAtlas is an open-source local email I/O layer for AI agents and Python applications. Ingest .eml files, mbox archives, and IMAP folders, export documents, and send outbound email with local audit records."
>
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
      <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <span>MailAtlas</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="topnav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="#why">Why</a>
      <a href="#sources">Sources</a>
      <a href="#stores">Stored data</a>
      <a href="/docs/">Docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="landing-main">
    <section class="hero" id="overview">
      <div class="hero-artifact" aria-hidden="true">
        <span>Subject:</span>
        <span>From: alice@example.com</span>
        <span>$ mailatlas ingest</span>
        <span>Content-Type: text/html</span>
        <span>attachment.pdf</span>
        <span>Message-ID:</span>
        <span>mbox://archive.2024</span>
        <span>outbound/raw</span>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Open-source local email I/O</p>
        <h1>MailAtlas</h1>
        <p class="hero-subhead">Local email I/O for AI agents and data apps.</p>
        <p class="lede">
          MailAtlas turns <code>.eml</code> files, <code>mbox</code> archives, selected IMAP folders,
          and outbound sends into one local, inspectable workspace. It preserves raw messages,
          cleaned text, normalized HTML, extracted assets, metadata, exports, and outbound audit
          records so software can read, search, export, send, and audit email without relying on a
          hosted mailbox service.
        </p>
        <p class="lede lede-tight">
          MailAtlas is built for developers who need email to behave like structured local data, not
          like a browser UI.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Primary actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Start with files</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions hero-actions-secondary" aria-label="Secondary actions">
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Connect IMAP</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Configure outbound email</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">View GitHub</a>
        </div>
        <p class="hero-command"><code>python -m pip install mailatlas</code></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="why">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Why MailAtlas</p>
        <h2>Email should be local software state, not only an inbox UI.</h2>
        <p>
          AI agents and data applications often need to work with email, but the default path is
          still a human inbox interface. Browser automation can read email, but it is slow, fragile,
          expensive, and difficult to audit.
        </p>
        <p>
          MailAtlas gives AI agents and software systems a direct local representation of email. It
          keeps original messages and processed views together so your application can use the
          cheapest useful representation first and inspect higher-fidelity artifacts when needed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Use MailAtlas when you need to</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Build an email corpus for retrieval, analytics, or AI agent workflows.</li>
            <li>Preserve links between cleaned text, HTML, raw email, and attachments.</li>
            <li>Process mailbox exports without running a server.</li>
            <li>Pull selected IMAP folders on demand.</li>
            <li>Send email through configured providers while keeping a local audit trail.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="story">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
        <h2>Bring email in, preserve provenance, export or send from the same workspace.</h2>
      </div>

      <ol class="step-list">
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Bring email in</h3>
            <p>
              Point MailAtlas at saved <code>.eml</code> files, an <code>mbox</code> archive, or
              selected folders in an IMAP mailbox. For live mailboxes, run manual sync when you want
              to fetch new messages.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Preserve provenance</h3>
            <p>
              MailAtlas stores original message bytes alongside cleaned text, normalized HTML,
              extracted inline images, regular attachments, source metadata, and parser notes. The
              stored document remains traceable back to the input that produced it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Export or build on it</h3>
            <p>
              Use the CLI, Python API, or MCP server to list documents, inspect one document, export
              JSON, Markdown, HTML, or PDF, or build your own workflow on top of the workspace.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">04</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Send with an audit trail</h3>
            <p>
              When your application sends email, MailAtlas can render the message, store an outbound
              record, copy attachments, preserve provider status, and send through SMTP, Cloudflare
              Email Service, or Gmail API OAuth.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="sources">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Sources and sinks</p>
        <h2>Choose where your email lives.</h2>
        <p>
          Start with one path and add others later. Everything lands in the same local workspace.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Files</strong>
          <span>
            Use file ingest when you already have individual email messages or directories of
            exported messages.
          </span>
          <code>.eml</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/examples/mbox-ingest/">
          <strong>Archive</strong>
          <span>
            Use <code>mbox</code> ingest when you have a mailbox export on disk.
          </span>
          <code>mbox</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Mailbox</strong>
          <span>
            Use manual IMAP sync when messages are still in a live mailbox.
          </span>
          <code>sync</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>
            Use outbound email when your application needs to send and audit messages.
          </span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="try">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Try it</p>
        <h2>Start with a local workspace and one message file.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="terminal">
        <div class="terminal-bar">
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <code>~/work</code>
        </div>
        <pre><code>python3.12 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
python -m pip install mailatlas

export MAILATLAS_HOME="$PWD/.mailatlas"
mailatlas ingest path/to/message.eml
mailatlas list</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="terminal terminal-secondary">
        <div class="terminal-bar">
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <span></span>
          <code>sample fixtures</code>
        </div>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/mailatlas/sample-data.git
mailatlas ingest sample-data/fixtures/eml/atlas-market-map.eml
mailatlas list</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="stores">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">What MailAtlas stores</p>
        <h2>A workspace contains ordinary local files and SQLite metadata.</h2>
        <p>
          Provider credentials are read at runtime. MailAtlas does not write SMTP passwords,
          Cloudflare API tokens, IMAP passwords, Gmail tokens, or OAuth access tokens into the
          workspace database, raw snapshots, logs, or JSON send results.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list storage-list">
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Inbound</strong>
          <span>Original raw email bytes, cleaned body text, normalized HTML snapshots, and metadata.</span>
          <code>raw/html</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Assets</strong>
          <span>Extracted inline images and regular file attachments associated with a document.</span>
          <code>assets</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Exports</strong>
          <span>JSON, Markdown, HTML, and PDF artifacts written from stored documents.</span>
          <code>exports</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Mailbox sync</strong>
          <span>IMAP sync cursors for manual selected-folder sync.</span>
          <code>SQLite</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>
            Outbound <code>.eml</code> snapshots, body files, copied attachments, recipient metadata,
            provider status, and retry metadata.
          </span>
          <code>outbound</code>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-fit" id="fit">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Is MailAtlas for you?</p>
        <h2>Use it when local email artifacts matter. Use something else for hosted mail products.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Reach for MailAtlas when</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You are feeding email into an AI agent, retrieval system, notebook, or data app.</li>
            <li>You need raw, cleaned, structured, and visual views of the same message.</li>
            <li>You want to script over years of <code>.eml</code> or <code>mbox</code> data without a hosted service.</li>
            <li>You need manual IMAP sync into a local store.</li>
            <li>You need a local audit trail for email your application sends.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article>
          <h3>Use something else when</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You need a hosted inbox product or full webmail client.</li>
            <li>You need background mailbox sync as a managed service.</li>
            <li>You need deliverability management, campaign analytics, suppression lists, or marketing automation.</li>
            <li>You only need a low-level MIME parser and do not care about storage, exports, or provenance.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="next">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Next steps</p>
        <h2>Pick the first task you need to prove.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/installation/">
          <strong>Install MailAtlas</strong>
          <span>Set up the CLI and verify the install with <code>mailatlas doctor</code>.</span>
          <code>install</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Run the Quickstart</strong>
          <span>Ingest a local <code>.eml</code> file and export a stored document.</span>
          <code>files</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Sync a mailbox folder</strong>
          <span>Fetch selected IMAP folders into the same workspace.</span>
          <code>imap</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Configure outbound email</strong>
          <span>Render, store, and send messages through configured providers.</span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer-cta">
      <div class="footer-brand">
        <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>MailAtlas</span>
        </a>
        <p>MailAtlas is open-source local email I/O. Read the docs, install it, and keep your mail where you can inspect it.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <nav class="footer-links" aria-label="Footer">
        <div>
          <h2>Docs</h2>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Quickstart</a>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Manual IMAP Sync</a>
          <a href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Outbound Email</a>
          <a href="/docs/concepts/workspace-model/">Workspace Model</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Project</h2>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/examples">Examples</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/sample-data">Sample Data</a>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/roadmap/">Roadmap</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Trust</h2>
          <a href="/docs/marketing/security-and-privacy/">Security and Privacy</a>
          <a href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas/issues">Issues</a>
        </div>
      </nav>

      <div class="footer-bottom">
        <span>© 2026 MailAtlas. MIT licensed.</span>
        <span>local-first</span>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </main>
</MarketingLayout>
